Description: A woman sleeping, seated on a step in front of a building, her chin on her left hand and resting her elbow in her other hand, in her lap, wearing a gown, shawl and scarf around her head; with an urn behind to right; after an etching by Parmigianino (Bartsch 10). Chiaroscuro woodcut printed from two blocks in black and ochre
Producer name: Print made by: John Baptist Jackson
Curator's comments: Jackson later added a dedication to the Society of Antiquaries of London, in around 1750, with six lines of Italian verse.
Bibliographic references: Kainen 1962 / John Baptist Jackson, 18thc. master of the color woodcut (5)
Associated names: Representation of: St Thais of Egypt (?)
Previous owner: Previous owner/ex-collection: James Franck Bright (sale Sotheby's 26/8.vi.1918/455)
Acquisition notes: The run of prints from 1918,0713.9 through to 73 all come from two albums of colour woodcuts formed by Consul Smith in Venice in the second quarter of the XVIIIc. They were broken up at the sale at Sotheby's 26-28 June 1918 of the collection of the Rev. James Franck Bright, DD, late Master of University College Oxford, and formerly collected by Dr Richard Bright, MD. Colnaghi acted as the BM's agent, and Dodgson put together a group of donors who presented individual prints; these were purchased outright, while the rest were exchanged for duplicates.
